{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"637d04ac-28d1-47e4-92e8-587a22a5fdfa","content":"Use `dotnet watch test` — it monitors your files and re-runs tests automatically on save:\n\n```\ndotnet watch test --filter \"RemoveStock_ExceedsAvailable_ThrowsException\"\n```\n\nThe `--filter` flag limits re-runs to just your failing test for faster feedback. Once it's fixed, remove the filter to run all tests.\n\n**About your failing test:** `RemoveStock` doesn't validate stock levels — it just subtracts without throwing. You'll need to add a guard in `RemoveStock`:\n\n```csharp\npublic void RemoveStock(string sku, int quantity)\n{\n    var current = _stock.GetValueOrDefault(sku);\n    if (quantity > current)\n        throw new InvalidOperationException(\"Insufficient stock\");\n    _stock[sku] = current - quantity;\n}\n```\n\nWant me to apply the fix and start the watch?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"62bff055-0c2c-4ba4-aff5-bf4c8c68b1a6","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to set up hot reload for their test project. Since this is using Microsoft.Testing.Platform (as indicated in global.json) with .NET 10, they can use `dotnet test --hotreload` or `dotnet watch test`.\n\nLet me check what's available. With `dotnet watch`, they can run tests in watch mode. Let me verify.\n\nActually, the newer Microsoft.Testing.Platform supports `dotnet test --hotreload` in .NET 10. But the more traditional approach is `dotnet watch test`.\n\nLet me just set it up using `dotnet watch test` which will re-run tests when files change. That's the standard hot reload approach for test projects.\n\n\nI'll go ahead and show them the setup with `dotnet watch test` since that's the most straightforward approach.","outputTokens":439,"requestId":"A038:350962:19FBDF8:1D6FD3C:69FE909C"},"id":"46813ab0-29ce-4748-8d20-9df1510636dc","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:40:55.621Z","parentId":"97caa861-0407-4e86-931a-1c19a4e0a45a"}
